    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "That specific sensitivity to your location within your own home is actually a very common and helpful feature, not a sign of a hidden stalker. Most modern routers use a technology called \"Signal Strength\" or \"RSSI\" to automatically adjust their broadcast power based on the walls between you and the device, ensuring a strong connection regardless of where you stand. This is why you see it get stronger in the kitchen (closer to the router) and weaker in the bedroom (blocked by walls), and it is a standard part of how Wi-Fi works, not a targeted tracking attempt. You are simply experiencing the normal physics of wireless signals interacting with your house's structure.",
